=== About Goshu Shrine ===
Oyora Shrine was founded on November 1st, {{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|WD=Q2048|1=1907}} (Meiji 40). Five shrines are enshrined together: Nunotahime Shrine (formerly {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Mukakusha|1=UNKNOWN}}), Yamauchi Shrine (formerly Murasha), and Doso Shrine (formerly Mukakusha). The next two shrines, Kusatsu Otoshi Shrine and Nunotahime Shrine, will become Shikinai Shrines {{Sfn|Oyora Shrine 4-za (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1977}}.

; Kusatsu Otoshi Shrine
: ``Kusatsuooshijinja''. It was originally enshrined in Kanda, Niwa Village, Oaza Karita.
: ``Kusatsu Otoshi Shrine Kuwasizuku'' in Sumiyoshi District, Settsu Province in the ``Engishiki'' divine name book, and ``Nakatomi Sumuji no Kami'' in the annotation of the Sumiyoshi deity {{ill|lt=Mikogami|Q352176|WD=Q352176|1=Mikogami}} of the Sumiyoshi deity {{ill|lt=Mikogami|Q352176|WD=Q352176|1=Mikogami}} in the ``Sumiyoshi Taisha Jindaiki''. {{Sfn|Kusatsu Otoshi Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1977}} (Akaru Hime no Mikoto Shrine, Shikinai Shrine Research Report Vol. 5, edited by Shikinai Shrine Research Group, Shikinai Shrine Research Group, 1977.</ref>). The entry ``Kuwazuku'' in the Shinmeicho means that the imperial court dedicated a hoe and a sewage bolt during the annual prayer festival. During the Meiji period, it was listed as a former village shrine, but was later enshrined with Oyora Shrine.: However, regarding ``Kusatsu Otoshi Shrine'' in the Shinmeicho, there is a theory that it is Otoshi Shrine, which is the outer branch shrine of Sumiyoshi Taisha Shrine, as another Hideron shrine (the ``Shikiuchi Shrine Investigation Report'' considers the former Kusatsu Otoshi Shrine in Karita to be more likely) {{Sfn|Kusatsu Otoshi Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1977}}.
; Nunotahime Shrine
: "Nunotahimejinja". It is said that it was originally enshrined in Sugimoto VillageAza Nukunota, but its location is currently unknown.
: It is compared to ``Tsunotahime no Mikoto Shrine'' in Sumiyoshi District, Settsu Province in the ``Engishiki'' divine name book, and to ``Nunotahime no Kami'' of the Sumiyoshi no Mikogami in ``Sumiyoshi Taisha Jindaiki.'' There is a theory that the god's name means the god of ``Nono-no-ta'' (rice fields) {{Sfn|Tsunotahime no Mikoto Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1977}}. During the Meiji period, it remained as a small shrine, and in 1872, it was listed as a former Mukakusha, but later it was enshrined with Oyora Shrine.

